3nd.title: Logarithm

3y1.title: Data capacity
3y1.text:
The data capacity of an object is the [3nd] of the number of different distinguishable states the object can be placed into. For example, a coin that can be placed heads or tails has a data capacity of $\log(2)$ units of [data]. The choice of [logarithm_base base] for the logarithm determines the unit of data; common units include the [3p0], [nat], and [3wn] (corresponding to base 2, e, and 10). For example, the coin has a data capacity of $\log_2(2)=1$ bit, and a pair of two dice (which can be placed into 36 distinguishable states) have a data capacity of $\log_2(36) \approx 5.17$ bits. Note that the data capacity of a channel depends on the ability of an observer to distinguish different states of the object: If the coin is a penny, and I'm able to tell whether you placed the image of Abraham Lincoln facing North, South, West, or East (regardless of whether the coin is heads or tails), then that coin has a data capacity of $\log_2(8) = 3$ bits when used to transmit a message from you to me.

The data capacity of an object is closely related to the [channel_capacity channel capacity] of a [communications_channel communications channel]. The difference is that the channel capacity is the amount of data the channel can transmit per unit time (measured, e.g., in bits per second), while the data capacity of an object is the amount of data that can be encoded by putting the object into a particular state (measured, e.g., in bits).

Why is the data capacity of an object the logarithm of the number of states? Because $n$ copies of an object carry $n$ times as much data, but can be placed into [exponential exponentially] more states. For example, one die can be placed 6 ways; two die can be placed $6^2=36$ ways; and $n$ die can be placed into $6^n$ ways. Data grows [linear linearly] as the number of distinguishable states grows exponentially, so data is logarithmic in the number of states. For more on this topic, see [data_is_logarithmic Data is logarithmic].

The data capacity of an object bounds the length of the message that you can send using that object. For example, it takes about 5 bits of data to encode a single letter A-Z, so if you want to transmit a 8-letter word to somebody, you need an object with a data capacity of about $5 \cdot 8 = 40$ bits. In other words, if you have 40 coins in a coin jar on your desk, and if we worked out an [encoding_scheme encoding scheme] (such as [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ASCII ASCII]) ahead of time, then you can tell me any 8-letter word using those coins.

[+3qq] is agnostic about what it means to say that you "can" place the coins into a number of different states, and it also remains agnostic about what it means for me to be able to "distinguish" between them. Rather, _given_ a set of states that you claim you could put an object into, which you claim I can distinguish, information theory can tell you how to use those objects in a clever way to send messages to me. For more on what it means for two physical subsystems to communicate with each other by encoding messages into their environment, see [communication Communication].

Note that the amount of [3xd] carried by an object is not generally equal to the data capacity of the object. For example, say a trusted mutual friend of ours places a coin "heads" if your eyes are blue and "tails" otherwise. If I already know what color your eyes are, then the state of the coin doesn't carry any information for me. If instead I was very sure that your eyes are blue, but actually you've been wearing blue contact lenses and your eyes are really brown, then the coin may carry quite a bit more than 1 bit of information for me. In other words, the amount of information that is actually carried by an object is subjective; see [ Information is subjective].

The amount of subjective information carried by an object to me (measured in [shannon shannons]) may be either more or less than its data capacity. (More if the message is very surprising to me, less if I already knew the message in advance.) The relationship between the data capacity of an object and the amount of information it carries to me is that the data capacity of the object is the maximum amount of information I can [expectation expect] to gain by observing the object. For more, see [ Information and data capacity].
